<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[826,1473,1049,1782]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">
<taxonomicName authority="(Orla-Jensen, 1919)" authorityName="Weiss et al." authorityYear="1984" baseAuthorityName="Orla-Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[828,1269,1088,1112]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="subSpecies" species="delbrueckii" subSpecies="bulgaricus">
<emphasis box="[828,1083,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">Lactobacillus delbrueckii</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[1161,1269,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">bulgaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(bul.ga’ri.cus. N.L. masc. adj. 
<taxonomicName authority=", Bulgarian" authorityName="Bulgarian" box="[939,1168,1120,1144]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="bulgaricus">
<emphasis box="[939,1047,1120,1144]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">bulgaricus</emphasis>
, Bulgarian
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="11.[826,1473,1049,1782]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">
Strains of this subspecies were previously referred to as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">
<taxonomicName authority="(Orla-Jensen, 1919)" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="bulgaricus">L. bulgaricus</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Orla-Jensen, 1919)" authorityName="Weiss et al." authorityYear="1984" baseAuthorityName="Orla-Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[951,1284,1197,1221]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="subSpecies" species="delbrueckii" subSpecies="bulgaricus">L. delbrueckii subsp. bulgaricus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
ferment glucose to D(−)-lactic acid and also metabolise fructose, mannose and lactose, but not sucrose [
<bibRefCitation author="Weiss N &amp; Schillinger U &amp; Kandler O." box="[1152,1182,1260,1284]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" pagination="552 - 557" refId="ref62055" refString="60. Weiss N, Schillinger U, Kandler O. Lactobacillus lactis, Lactobacillus leichmannii and Lactobacillus bulgaricus, subjective synonyms of Lactobacillus delbrueckii, and description of Lactobacillus delbrueckii subsp. lactis comb. nov. and Lactobacillus delbrueckii subsp. bulgaricus comb. nov. Syst Appl Microbiol 1983; 4: 552 - 557." type="journal article" year="1983">60</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rogosa M &amp; Wiseman RF &amp; Mitchell JA &amp; Disraely MN &amp; Beaman AJ" box="[1195,1225,1260,1284]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" pagination="681 - 699" refId="ref62114" refString="61. Rogosa M, Wiseman RF, Mitchell JA, Disraely MN, Beaman AJ. Species differentiation of oral lactobacilli from man including descriptions of Lactobacillus salivarius nov spec and Lactobacillus cellobiosus nov spec. J Bacteriol 1953; 65: 681 - 699." type="journal article" year="1953">61</bibRefCitation>
]. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Orla-Jensen, 1919)" authorityName="Weiss et al." authorityYear="1984" baseAuthorityName="Orla-Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1919" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="subSpecies" species="delbrueckii" subSpecies="bulgaricus">
<emphasis box="[1245,1391,1260,1284]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">L. delbrueckii</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[828,936,1291,1315]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">bulgaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
undergoes genome reduction which particularly relates to loss or silencing of genes coding for metabolism of carbohydrates [
<bibRefCitation author="van de Guchte M &amp; Penaud S &amp; Grimaldi C &amp; Barbe V" box="[987,1018,1353,1377]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" pagination="9274 - 9279" refId="ref61936" refString="57. van de Guchte M, Penaud S, Grimaldi C, Barbe V, Bryson K et al. The complete genome sequence of Lactobacillus bulgaricus reveals extensive and ongoing reductive evolution. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 2006; 103: 9274 - 9279." type="journal article" year="2006">57</bibRefCitation>
]. The genome size is 1.76 Mbp and the G+C content of DNA is 49.9 mol%.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[826,1473,1049,1782]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793">
Isolated from yoghurt and cheese and an important starter cultures in the production of these foods [
<bibRefCitation author="Ganzle MG" box="[1296,1326,1462,1486]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" pagination="855 - 900" refId="ref61986" refString="58. Ganzle MG. Fermented Foods. In: Doyle MP, Diez Gonzalez F, Hill C (editors). Food Microbiol. Fundam. Front, 5 th ed. ASM Press; 2019. pp. 855 - 900." type="book chapter" year="2019">58</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hutkins RW" box="[1338,1367,1462,1486]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" refId="ref62031" refString="59. Hutkins RW. Microbiology and technology of fermented foods, 2 nd. Chigaco, IL: IFT Press; 2019." type="book" year="2019">59</bibRefCitation>
] but also detected by culture-independent methodology in the intestinal microbiota of suckling piglets [
<bibRefCitation author="Wang W &amp; Hu H &amp; Zijlstra RT &amp; Zheng J &amp; Ganzle MG" box="[1210,1242,1525,1549]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2793" pagination="48" refId="ref61816" refString="54. Wang W, Hu H, Zijlstra RT, Zheng J, Ganzle MG. Metagenomic reconstructions of gut microbial metabolism in weanling pigs. Microbiome 2019; 7: 48." type="journal article" year="2019">54</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
